## 📊 PRODUCT STRATEGY: GOVERNANCE-FIRST POSITIONING

### What We Are (Core Identity)

```yaml
Governance Layer:
  ✅ Enforces SDLC 4.9 quality gates (G0.1-G9, 11 gates total)
  ✅ Automates validation using Policy-as-Code (OPA)
  ✅ Provides permanent audit trail (Evidence Vault, SHA256 integrity)
  ✅ Multi-approval workflow (CEO, CTO, CPO, CIO, CFO approval)

Key Differentiation:
  - FIRST platform on SDLC 4.9 (10-stage complete lifecycle)
  - Policy-as-Code engine (100+ pre-built policies)
  - Evidence Vault (3+ years trust moat)
  - Bridge-First strategy (low adoption friction)
```

### What We're NOT (Anti-Patterns)

```yaml
❌ NOT a project management tool:
   - We don't replace Jira, Linear, GitHub
   - We don't manage sprints or track tasks
   - We enforce gates, not manage work

❌ NOT a code repository:
   - We integrate with GitHub (read-only sync)
   - We don't store code, we validate it

❌ NOT a CI/CD pipeline:
   - We sit on top of GitHub Actions/GitLab CI
   - We validate deployments, not run them
```

### Target Users (ICP - Ideal Customer Profile)

```yaml
Primary Persona: Engineering Manager
  Team Size: 6-50 engineers
  Pain: 60-70% feature waste, low adoption (32% BFlow, 60% NQH)
  Budget: $10K-$100K/year
  Decision: 30-60 days
  Success: Feature adoption 32% → 70%+

Secondary Persona: CTO (Enterprise)
  Company: 50-500 engineers
  Pain: Failed SOC 2 audit (no compliance evidence)
  Budget: $100K-$500K/year
  Decision: 90-180 days
  Success: SOC 2 certification in 3 months (vs 12 months)

Tertiary Persona: DevOps Engineer
  Team: CI/CD automation focus
  Pain: Manual quality checks slow releases
  Budget: $5K-$50K/year
  Decision: 14-30 days
  Success: DORA metrics improved (Deployment Frequency, Lead Time)
```

