### 3. Competitive Analysis

```markdown
Cmd+K Prompt:
"Compare SDLC Orchestrator vs [COMPETITOR] on:
- Category (PM tool, CI/CD, governance)
- Coverage (4-stage pipeline vs 10-stage SDLC)
- Pricing (free, $99/mo, $499/mo, $2499/mo)
- Key features (what they have that we don't)
- Our moat (what we have that they can't copy in <18 months)
- Threats (how they could attack us)
- Opportunities (market gaps we should exploit)"

Example:
---
SDLC Orchestrator vs Jira

Category:
  Jira: Project management tool (task execution, 10-20% lifecycle)
  SDLC Orchestrator: Governance platform (quality gates, 100% lifecycle)

Coverage:
  Jira: Task tracking (WHAT you're building)
  SDLC Orchestrator: Gate enforcement (WHY, HOW, WHO approved)

Pricing:
  Jira: $7.75/user/mo (Standard), $15.25/user/mo (Premium)
  SDLC Orchestrator: $99/mo (Lite, 10 users), $499/mo (Standard, 50 users)

Key Features (Jira has, we don't):
  ✅ Native board (we defer to v2, Bridge-First for MVP)
  ✅ 1000+ integrations (we focus on GitHub, expand later)
  ✅ Mobile app (we web-first, mobile later)

Our Moat (we have, Jira doesn't):
  ✅ SDLC 4.9 enforcement (6-12 months for Jira to understand)
  ✅ Policy-as-Code (OPA integration, 1-2 years to replicate)
  ✅ Evidence Vault (permanent audit trail, 3+ years trust moat)
  ✅ Design Thinking gates (G0.1, G0.2 - Jira has no validation)

Threats:
  ⚠️ Jira adds "Governance module" (leverages 10M+ user base)
  ⚠️ Jira partners with compliance vendor (e.g., Vanta, Drata)

Opportunities:
  🚀 Jira users frustrated with lack of quality gates
  🚀 Enterprise buyers need SOC 2 evidence (Jira doesn't provide)
  🚀 Design Thinking adoption growing (we're only platform with gates)
---
```

